revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox religious biography | honorific-prefix = [[Acharya]] Shri 108 | honorific-suffix = Ji Maharaj | image = Aklank swami.jpg | alt = Akalanka | caption = Image of ''Acharya Akalanka'' | religion = [[Jainism]] | sect = [[Digambara]] | birth_date = 720 CE | death_date = 780CE | initiator = }} {{Jainism}} '''Akalanka''' (also known as ''Akalank Deva'' and ''Bhatta Akalanka'') was a famous Jain logician whose [[Sanskrit]]-language works are seen as landmarks in Indian logic.<ref name=Book/><ref>{{cite book |author=Ganga Ram Garg |title=Encyclopaedia of the Hindu World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WjDcd0cTFxQC&pg=PA288 |year=1992 |publisher=Concept |isbn=978-81-7022-375-7 |page=288 }}</ref> He lived from 720-780 A.D. and belonged to the [[Digambara]] sect of [[Jainism]].<ref name=Book>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=64HXAAAAMAAJ|title=The Enlightened Vision of the Self|isbn=9788170272441|author1=Akalaṅka|first1=|last2=Goyal|first2=Devendra Kumar|date=2005-01-01|p=1,2}}</ref>{{sfn|Singh|Baruah|2003|p=9}} His work ''Astasati'', a commentary on ''[[Aptamimamsa]]'' of [[Acharya Samantabhadra]] deals mainly with ''jaina'' logic. He was a contemporary of [[Rashtrakuta]] king [[Krishna I]]. He is the author of Tattvārtharājavārtika, a commentary on major Jain text ''[[Tattvartha Sutra]]''. He greatly contributed to the development of the philosophy of ''[[Anekantavada]]'' and is therefore called the "Master of Jain logic".{{sfn|Singh|Baruah|2003|p=110}}{{sfn|Singh|Mishra|2007|pp=9–13}}
==Biography== The great eighth-century logician Akalanka was aware of the contents of the ''Angas'', although it cannot be said whether they represent an idea rather than a reality for him, and he also seems to have been the first [[Digambara]] to have introduced as a valid form of scriptural classification the division into ''kalika'' and ''utkalika'' texts which was also employed by the [[Svetambara]]s.{{sfn|Dundas|2002|p=80}}
==Works==
The following Sanskrit-language works are attributed to Akalanka. Some of these are:{{sfn|Singh|Baruah|2003|p=32}}<ref>{{cite book |author=Sures Chandra Banerji |title=A Companion to Sanskrit Literature |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JkOAEdIsdUsC&pg=PA10 |year=1989 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-0063-2 |page=10 }}</ref>
* ''Laghiyastraya'' * ''Pramānasangraha'' * ''Nyāyaviniscaya-vivarana'' * ''Siddhiviniscaya-vivarana'' * ''Astasati'' * ''Tattvārtharājavārtika''
