'''Kingi Areta Keiha''' (24 December 1900&ndash;29 May 1961) was a New Zealand law clerk, interpreter, soldier, Maori welfare officer and farmer. Of [[Māori people|Māori]] descent, he identified with the [[Rongowhakaata]], [[Te Aitanga-a-Hauiti]] and [[Te Aitanga-a-Mahaki]] [[iwi]]. He was born in [[Gisborne, New Zealand|Gisborne]], [[North Island|East Coast]], [[New Zealand]] on 24 December 1900. His father was Mikaere (Mikaera) Pare Keiha Turangi, brother of [[Heni Materoa Carroll]], who was married to Sir [[James Carroll (New Zealand politician)|James Carroll]].<ref name="DNZB Keiha">{{DNZB|title=Kingi Areta Keiha|first= Maata Rewanga|last= Keiha|id=5k6|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref>
He reached battalion command of the [[28th Maori Battalion]] during its last action in North Africa.
