{{Infobox language |name=Língua Geral |altname=Tupi Austral |nativename= |states=[[Brazil]] |era=17th–18th centuries |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Tupian languages|Tupian]] |fam2=[[Tupi–Guarani languages|Tupi–Guarani]] |fam3=Tupi languages |fam4=[[Tupi language|Tupi]] |iso3=none |linglist= |glotto=none |notice=IPA }}
The '''Língua Geral Paulista''' (São Paulo General language), or '''Tupí Austral''' (Southern Tupi), was a [[Tupi language|Tupi]]-based [[trade language]] of [[São Vicente, São Paulo]], and the upper [[Tietê River]]. In the 17th century, it was widely spoken in [[São Paulo]] and spread to neighboring regions. Starting in 1750, orders from [[Sebastião José de Carvalho e Melo, 1st Marquess of Pombal|Marquis of Pombal]] forced Portuguese to be taught to Brazilian children in schools. Língua Geral Paulista subsequently lost ground to Portuguese and eventually became extinct.
